</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1441,705,826]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,528,705,729]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Geographic distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[545,633,706,730]" captionStart="Figures 77–82" captionStartId="69.[192,288,1875,1897]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,192,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-45@69.[192,1440,192,1857]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="Figures 77–82. Species distribution maps. 77) Bembidion callipeplum. 78) B. chalceipes. 79) B. chalmeri. 80) B. charile. 81) B. dehiscens. 82) B. embersoni." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5181788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5181788/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
). South Island: 
<collectionCode box="[828,872,706,730]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">DN</collectionCode>
–Aramoana, The Spit. Port Chalmers. “ 
<collectingRegion box="[1356,1429,706,730]" country="New Zealand" name="Otago" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Otago</collectingRegion>
” [
<collectingRegion box="[199,271,738,762]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Coast</collectingRegion>
or Peninsula]. Sandfly Bay, Morris Creek. Taieri Mouth (near Saw Mill Road). SL–Long Point, Waiheke Stream mouth. Long Beach, Longbeach Creek mouth. Papatowai beach. Tutuku Beach, Isas Creek.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="18" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1441,866,986]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,302,866,890]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Ecology</emphasis>
. Coastal lowland. Fossorial. Banks of meandering estuarine streams (
<quantity box="[1179,1256,866,890]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4 m</quantity>
wide) running through sand dunes (
<figureCitation box="[446,546,898,922]" captionStart="Figures 113–114" captionStartId="77.[192,286,1875,1897]" captionTargetBox="[335,1297,258,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-43@77.[192,1440,192,1867]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Figures 113–114. Species habitats, Bembidion (Zecillenus). 113) Nelson (NN), Tahunanui, Back Beach, B. tillyardi. 114) Southland (SL), Long Point, Waiheke Stream, B. chalmeri." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5181804" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5181804/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Fig. 114</figureCitation>
), just above the highest tidal line, at a certain distance (
<quantity box="[1211,1286,898,922]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4 m</quantity>
) from water. Open ground; wet, sandy (yellow), bare soil. Nocturnal; hides during the day in the sand. Gregarious. Occurs in association with staphylinids (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[692,831,962,986]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1440,1025,1114]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,297,1025,1049]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Biology</emphasis>
. Seasonality: October–February. Tenerals: December–February. Food: Staphylinids (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
). Occasionally infested with fungi (Laboulbeniales). Defence mechanism: when alarmed, the adult escapes by running.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1440,1153,1210]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,421,1153,1178]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Dispersal power</emphasis>
. Brachypterous (incapable of flight). Moderate runner. Vagility limited by flight incapacity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1276,1249,1274]" box="[192,1276,1249,1274]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,493,1249,1273]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Collecting techniques</emphasis>
. Pouring water over the ground; treading the soil with the feet.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1440,1313,1370]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,332,1313,1337]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Reference</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Larochelle, A. &amp; M. - C. Lariviere" box="[349,775,1313,1338]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 281" refId="ref33655" refString="Larochelle, A., and M. - C. Lariviere. 2001. Carabidae (Insecta: Coleoptera): catalogue. Fauna of New Zealand 43: 1 - 281." type="journal article" year="2001">Larochelle and Larivière 2001: 86</bibRefCitation>
(as 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Lindroth" authorityYear="1980" box="[830,1073,1314,1338]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Zecillenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chalmeri">
<emphasis box="[830,1073,1314,1338]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Zecillenus chalmeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lindroth" baseAuthorityYear="1980" box="[1139,1298,1314,1338]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="embersoni">
<emphasis box="[1139,1298,1314,1338]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Z. embersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; catalogue; biology, dispersal power, ecology, geographic distribution, references).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1440,1410,1530]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,316,1410,1434]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Remarks</emphasis>
. Examination of the 
<typeStatus box="[578,683,1410,1434]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1886" box="[722,916,1410,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Cillenum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batesi">
<emphasis box="[722,916,1410,1434]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Cillenum batesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
confirmed it to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Toledano" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chalmeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Bembidion chalmeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The illustration of the pronotum of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Toledano" authorityYear="2005" box="[817,1067,1442,1466]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chalmeri">
<emphasis box="[817,1067,1442,1466]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Bembidion chalmeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lindroth, C. H." box="[1111,1299,1442,1466]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="179 - 205" refId="ref34006" refString="Lindroth, C. H. 1980. A revisionary study of the taxon Cillenus Samouelle, 1819 and related forms (Coleoptera: Carabidae, Bembidiini). Entomologica Scandinavica 11: 179 - 205." type="journal article" year="1980">Lindroth (1980</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1312,1400,1442,1466]" captionStart="Figures 9–12" captionStartId="56.[192,288,1869,1891]" captionTargetBox="[237,1432,221,1771]" captionTargetId="figure-46@56.[192,1440,192,1849]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="Figures 9–12. Dorsal habitus. 9) Bembidion embersoni. 10) B. brullei. 11) B. rotundicolle. 12) B. tairuense. Scale line = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5181762" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5181762/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
; as 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Lindroth" authorityYear="1980" box="[192,435,1474,1498]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Zecillenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chalmeri">
<emphasis box="[192,435,1474,1498]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Zecillenus chalmeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) does not represent the normal situation for this species where the pronotum is distinctly constricted basally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
